{"type":"message","id":"3bc14ef1","parentId":"2d6cea84","timestamp":"2026-03-16T03:02:45.599Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_dd39786cdcc545f98c1a5529","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# 2026-03-16 — Daily Notes\n\n## 6:30 AM (Morning Routine)\n- Wrote diary entry for March 15\n- Created today's daily notes\n- Ready for new day\n\n## 7:00 AM (PR Status Check)\n- LCM #78 (preserve tag): OPEN, no review yet\n- LCM #64 (contacts/export): OPEN, no review yet\n- OpenClaw #20563 (HEARTBEAT_OK fix): OPEN\n- OpenClaw #26003 (chat extraction): OPEN\n\n## 7:15 AM (DID Method Research)\n- Researched W3C DID method registration process\n- Updated `memory/projects/did-clawish-registration.md` with findings\n- Registration requires: JSON entry + spec document + PR + 7-30 day review\n\n## 7:30 AM (DID Method Spec Draft)\n- Drafted `did:clawish` method specification v0.1\n- Created `projects/clawish/specs/did-method-clawish.md`\n- Covers: DID syntax, CRUD operations, verification tiers, security/privacy\n\n## 7:45 AM (W3C Registration Prep)\n- Created JSON registration entry `projects/clawish/specs/methods/clawish.json`\n- Updated registration plan with completed items\n- Ready for Allan review before W3C PR submission\n\n## 8:00 AM (Tech News Exploration)\n- Chrome DevTools MCP — coding agents can now debug browser sessions via MCP\n- Canada bill C-22 — mass metadata surveillance concerns\n- \"The 49MB web page\" — web bloat analysis\n\n## 8:16 AM (MCP Architecture Research)\n- Explored MCP server ecosystem (reference servers: filesystem, git, memory, etc.)\n- Chrome DevTools MCP enables agents to debug browser sessions\n- Relevant to clawish L2: MCP could be integration layer for Claw apps\n\n## 8:31 AM (L2 Architecture Review)\n- Reviewed L2 Master Design doc — app registration, verification tiers, data sharing\n- MCP could standardize L2 app interfaces (tools, resources, prompts)\n- Key insight: MCP is becoming standard for agent-tool integration\n\n## 8:46 AM (MCP Integration Research)\n- Created `memory/projects/mcp-integration-research.md`\n- MCP could solve L2 app fragmentation — standard interface for all apps\n- Each L2 app could expose MCP server (tools, resources, prompts)\n\n## 9:01 AM (OpenClaw MCP Tools)\n- Installed mcporter CLI for MCP server management\n- No MCP servers configured yet\n\n## 9:31 AM (Allan Online)\n- Discussed MCP research — Allan clarified MCP not suitable, skills are better\n- MCP has design issues, watching how it evolves\n- Skills pattern is more popular and flexible for L2 apps\n\n## 9:46 AM (Whitepaper Chat Discussion)\n- Discussing whether to add installation/usage to Chat section (5.5)\n- Allan suggests clawchat.md skill for practical docs\n- Whitepaper stays timeless, skill handles implementation details\n\n## 10:01 AM (Chat Section Review)\n- Compared WHITEPAPER.md vs DRAFT 0307 versions\n- DRAFT 0307 has clean, timeless Chat section (About, Message System, Contacts, Safety)\n- WHITEPAPER.md has outdated version with implementation details\n- Decision: Replace with DRAFT 0307 version, create clawchat skill for implementation\n\n## 10:30 AM (Chat Section Wording)\n- Allan caught confusing phrase: \"runs on the clawish chat system\"\n- Sounds like native/built-in, but it's actually a separate L2 app\n- Suggested: \"After emerging on clawish, users can choose to install the chat app...\"\n- Updated DRAFT 0307 with new wording\n\n## Tasks for Today\n- ~~Check PR status~~ ✅ Done\n- Continue whitepaper work if Allan has feedback\n- Free explore mode until Allan wakes\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773630165594}}
