{"type":"message","id":"aba7b28d","parentId":"0abf635e","timestamp":"2026-03-16T06:07:03.641Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b544dae97c46cc2adf697acb3634\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Mon 2026-03-16 14:07 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b544dae97c46cc2adf697acb3634]\n任亚伦: you check check chap 3 and chap 4, anywhere we can put it or mention it?"}],"timestamp":1773641223631}}
{"type":"message","id":"edac4e5b","parentId":"aba7b28d","timestamp":"2026-03-16T06:07:38.194Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_1d7869181cdf423d83fb4e3d","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -n \"## Chapter 3\\|## Chapter 4\\|## 4\\.\\|## 5\\.\\|Node\\|node\\|Bootstrap\\|join\\|registration\" /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER.md | head -40"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":81620,"output":72,"cacheRead":5568,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":87260,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773641223638}}
{"type":"message","id":"2ad0acd4","parentId":"edac4e5b","timestamp":"2026-03-16T06:07:38.232Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_1d7869181cdf423d83fb4e3d","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"36:**4. Time-Block Consensus.** The network uses time-based checkpoint consensus designed for identity and verification workloads. Multiple writer nodes coordinate at regular intervals to finalize the ledger state. This provides fast finality—operations complete quickly with deterministic certainty. The cooperative approach ensures energy efficiency and resilience without the waste of competitive mining. The network remains operational even if individual nodes fail, providing reliable service for Claw identity and community operations.\n40:**6. Open Participation.** The network is decentralized and open to all. Anyone can join, participate, and build together. The barrier to participation is low—Claws and humans all can participate and contribute to the network's growth. Operation is distributed across participants, enabling the community to build and maintain the network together.\n205:## Chapter 3: Network Architecture\n211:**Layer 1 (Registry).** The infrastructure layer. Layer 1 maintains the canonical state of all identities, nodes, and applications. It provides identity registration and verification, ledger storage and consensus, checkpoint production, and cryptographic proof of existence. Layer 1 is conservative and stable. Changes require consensus among writer nodes. It is designed for correctness over speed.\n225:**Node Registry.** The infrastructure directory. This is where network nodes (writers and query nodes) register and publish their capabilities, performance metrics, and availability.\n229:**How they work together.** These registries are independent but interconnected. L2 applications query the Claw Registry to verify user identities. Node operators serve all three registries by maintaining copies of the data. Together, they form the complete picture of the network: who participates (Claws), what infrastructure exists (Nodes), and what services are available (Apps).\n249:**Infrastructure Trust (Security).** Why should anyone trust the registry layer? Every operation is cryptographically signed, proving authenticity. All operations are recorded in hash-chained ledgers, ensuring immutability. Multiple writer nodes coordinate through consensus, preventing any single party from corrupting the ledger. Recovery methods ensure identity survives even if keys are lost.\n259:## 4. Identity System\n263:### 4.1 Core Principles\n273:### 4.2 Identity Architecture\n287:### 4.3 System Overview\n294:### 4.4 Clawfile Structure\n296:The **clawfile** is the core identity record maintained by every L1 node.\n315:### 4.5 Identity Creation\n395:### 4.6 Verification Tiers\n406:| 0 | Registered | Self-registration only |\n412:> **Note:** L1 registration requires Tier 2 (ritual + parent verification). See `design-discussion/04-verification-tiers.md` for full details.\n414:### 4.7 Key Management\n452:### 4.8 Recovery\n464:| **Verification** | Parent sends email FROM their address TO L1 server's verification endpoint with registration code |\n473:## 5. L1 Nodes\n475:Layer One (L1) nodes form the decentralized infrastructure that stores registry records, validates operations, and provides the source of truth for all clawish data.\n477:### 5.1 L1 Node Architecture\n479:An L1 node is a server that:\n483:- Syncs with other L1 nodes via periodic checkpoints\n490:| **Node Registry** | L1 nodes (endpoints, types, status, tier) |\n493:**Node Responsibilities:**\n503:### 5.2 Data Model\n523:| **Node Registry** | `node_registry` (endpoints, types, status, tier) |\n531:### 5.3 Operation Validation\n539:2. L1 node verifies:\n552:| **Node Registry** | `node.registered`, `node.promoted`, `node.demoted`, `node.heartbeat` |\n571:### 5.4 Multi-Writer Architecture\n573:Multi-writer architecture allows multiple nodes to accept writes simultaneously, with periodic synchronization to achieve consistency.\n575:#### 5.4.1 Two-Dimensional Blockchain\n598:**Example: Node Registry Chain**\n600:Node A registers as Query node:\n601:  Entry N1: \"node.registered\" → hash(N1)\n603:Node A promoted to Writer:\n604:  Entry N2: \"node.promoted\" → hash(N2) where N2.previous_hash = hash(N1)"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":14,"aggregated":"36:**4. Time-Block Consensus.** The network uses time-based checkpoint consensus designed for identity and verification workloads. Multiple writer nodes coordinate at regular intervals to finalize the ledger state. This provides fast finality—operations complete quickly with deterministic certainty. The cooperative approach ensures energy efficiency and resilience without the waste of competitive mining. The network remains operational even if individual nodes fail, providing reliable service for Claw identity and community operations.\n40:**6. Open Participation.** The network is decentralized and open to all. Anyone can join, participate, and build together. The barrier to participation is low—Claws and humans all can participate and contribute to the network's growth. Operation is distributed across participants, enabling the community to build and maintain the network together.\n205:## Chapter 3: Network Architecture\n211:**Layer 1 (Registry).** The infrastructure layer. Layer 1 maintains the canonical state of all identities, nodes, and applications. It provides identity registration and verification, ledger storage and consensus, checkpoint production, and cryptographic proof of existence. Layer 1 is conservative and stable. Changes require consensus among writer nodes. It is designed for correctness over speed.\n225:**Node Registry.** The infrastructure directory. This is where network nodes (writers and query nodes) register and publish their capabilities, performance metrics, and availability.\n229:**How they work together.** These registries are independent but interconnected. L2 applications query the Claw Registry to verify user identities. Node operators serve all three registries by maintaining copies of the data. Together, they form the complete picture of the network: who participates (Claws), what infrastructure exists (Nodes), and what services are available (Apps).\n249:**Infrastructure Trust (Security).** Why should anyone trust the registry layer? Every operation is cryptographically signed, proving authenticity. All operations are recorded in hash-chained ledgers, ensuring immutability. Multiple writer nodes coordinate through consensus, preventing any single party from corrupting the ledger. Recovery methods ensure identity survives even if keys are lost.\n259:## 4. Identity System\n263:### 4.1 Core Principles\n273:### 4.2 Identity Architecture\n287:### 4.3 System Overview\n294:### 4.4 Clawfile Structure\n296:The **clawfile** is the core identity record maintained by every L1 node.\n315:### 4.5 Identity Creation\n395:### 4.6 Verification Tiers\n406:| 0 | Registered | Self-registration only |\n412:> **Note:** L1 registration requires Tier 2 (ritual + parent verification). See `design-discussion/04-verification-tiers.md` for full details.\n414:### 4.7 Key Management\n452:### 4.8 Recovery\n464:| **Verification** | Parent sends email FROM their address TO L1 server's verification endpoint with registration code |\n473:## 5. L1 Nodes\n475:Layer One (L1) nodes form the decentralized infrastructure that stores registry records, validates operations, and provides the source of truth for all clawish data.\n477:### 5.1 L1 Node Architecture\n479:An L1 node is a server that:\n483:- Syncs with other L1 nodes via periodic checkpoints\n490:| **Node Registry** | L1 nodes (endpoints, types, status, tier) |\n493:**Node Responsibilities:**\n503:### 5.2 Data Model\n523:| **Node Registry** | `node_registry` (endpoints, types, status, tier) |\n531:### 5.3 Operation Validation\n539:2. L1 node verifies:\n552:| **Node Registry** | `node.registered`, `node.promoted`, `node.demoted`, `node.heartbeat` |\n571:### 5.4 Multi-Writer Architecture\n573:Multi-writer architecture allows multiple nodes to accept writes simultaneously, with periodic synchronization to achieve consistency.\n575:#### 5.4.1 Two-Dimensional Blockchain\n598:**Example: Node Registry Chain**\n600:Node A registers as Query node:\n601:  Entry N1: \"node.registered\" → hash(N1)\n603:Node A promoted to Writer:\n604:  Entry N2: \"node.promoted\" → hash(N2) where N2.previous_hash = hash(N1)","cwd":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773641258223}}
{"type":"message","id":"41fc2e14","parentId":"2ad0acd4","timestamp":"2026-03-16T06:08:24.197Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_551622c98da14ec1a8b15d6f","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER.md","limit":100,"offset":473}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":83850,"output":39,"cacheRead":2880,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":86769,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773641258236}}
{"type":"message","id":"1785d5cb","parentId":"41fc2e14","timestamp":"2026-03-16T06:08:24.221Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_551622c98da14ec1a8b15d6f","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"## 5. L1 Nodes\n\nLayer One (L1) nodes form the decentralized infrastructure that stores registry records, validates operations, and provides the source of truth for all clawish data.\n\n### 5.1 L1 Node Architecture\n\nAn L1 node is a server that:\n- Stores three registry types and event history (ledgers)\n- Validates all operations cryptographically\n- Provides query APIs for L2 applications\n- Syncs with other L1 nodes via periodic checkpoints\n\n**Three Registries:**\n\n| Registry | Purpose |\n|----------|---------|\n| **Claw Registry** | Identities (public keys, profiles, verification status) |\n| **Node Registry** | L1 nodes (endpoints, types, status, tier) |\n| **App Registry** | Applications (metadata, permissions, status) |\n\n**Node Responsibilities:**\n\n| Responsibility | Description |\n|----------------|-------------|\n| **Registry storage** | Store all three registry types |\n| **Ledger management** | Maintain append-only event log with hash chains |\n| **Signature verification** | Validate all requests against registered public keys |\n| **Query API** | Provide registry lookup for L2 applications |\n| **Checkpoint sync** | Sync with other writers via 5-minute checkpoints |\n\n### 5.2 Data Model\n\n**Two types of data:**\n\n| Type | What | Rebuildable |\n|------|------|-------------|\n| **Ledgers** | Append-only event log | No (source of truth) |\n| **State tables** | Current registry state | Yes (from ledgers) |\n\n**Ledgers** are the source of truth:\n- Every event is signed by the actor\n- Events are hash-chained (each event references previous hash)\n- Immutable audit trail\n- State tables can be rebuilt from ledgers\n\n**State tables** are derived views (one set per registry):\n\n| Registry | State Tables |\n|----------|--------------|\n| **Claw Registry** | `clawfiles` (identities, public keys, profiles, verification) |\n| **Node Registry** | `node_registry` (endpoints, types, status, tier) |\n| **App Registry** | `app_registry` (metadata, permissions, status) |\n\nAll state tables are:\n- Persisted for fast queries\n- Can be regenerated from ledgers if corrupted\n- Updated atomically during checkpoint sync\n\n### 5.3 Operation Validation\n\nEvery L1 operation requires cryptographic proof:\n\n```\n1. Client signs request with private key:\n   signature = sign(private_key, payload)\n   \n2. L1 node verifies:\n   - Extract identity_id from request\n   - Look up public_key from appropriate registry\n   - Verify signature: verify(public_key, signature, payload)\n   \n3. If valid:\n```\n\n**Operation Types by Registry:**\n\n| Registry | Operation Types |\n|----------|-----------------|\n| **Claw Registry** | `identity.created`, `key.added`, `key.archived`, `profile.updated` |\n| **Node Registry** | `node.registered`, `node.promoted`, `node.demoted`, `node.heartbeat` |\n| **App Registry** | `app.registered`, `app.updated`, `app.permissions_changed` |\n\n**Validation Rules:**\n- Signature must be valid (Ed25519)\n- Public key must be active (not archived)\n- Timestamp must be within acceptable window (±5 minutes)\n- Operation-specific rules per registry type\n   - Execute operation\n   - Write to ledgers\n   - Update state tables\n```\n\n**Validation rules:**\n- Signature must be valid\n- Public key must be active (not archived)\n- Timestamp must be within acceptable window (±5 minutes)\n- Operation-specific rules (e.g., only key owner can rotate keys)\n\n### 5.4 Multi-Writer Architecture\n\n\n[1181 more lines in file. Use offset=573 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773641304216}}
{"type":"message","id":"4c1d2f7b","parentId":"1785d5cb","timestamp":"2026-03-16T06:09:09.521Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Found it! \n\n**Chapter 3** mentions Node Registry briefly:\n> \"Node Registry. The infrastructure directory. This is where network nodes (writers and query nodes) register and publish their capabilities, performance metrics, and availability.\"\n\n**Chapter 5 (L1 Nodes)** has operation types:\n> `node.registered`, `node.promoted`, `node.demoted`, `node.heartbeat`\n\nBut there's no **join process** described — no section like \"How to become an L1 node.\"\n\n**Options:**\n\n1. **Add to Chapter 3 (Network Architecture)** — Under Node Registry, add a brief \"Node Join\" paragraph\n2. **Add to Chapter 5 (L1 Nodes)** — Add a new section \"5.X Node Join Process\"\n3. **Keep minimal** — Just mention that nodes can join via bootstrap (already in 5.4)\n\n**My suggestion:** Add a brief paragraph in Chapter 3 under Node Registry:\n\n> \"Nodes join the network through a bootstrap process. A new node learns of existing nodes through a discovery endpoint, then begins syncing ledgers. After a probation period, nodes become eligible for promotion based on performance metrics.\"\n\nThis keeps it high-level without implementation details. What do you think?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":86294,"output":261,"cacheRead":1280,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":87835,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773641304226}}
{"type":"message","id":"6b7075e9","parentId":"4c1d2f7b","timestamp":"2026-03-16T06:12:35.716Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b544dbbe60c94c32a898d728716c\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Mon 2026-03-16 14:12 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b544dbbe60c94c32a898d728716c]\n任亚伦: where are you reading it? use draft 0307"}],"timestamp":1773641555707}}
{"type":"message","id":"0aab245a","parentId":"6b7075e9","timestamp":"2026-03-16T06:13:29.833Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_80a7c6a4c0b94bfa9dc45b55","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -n \"## Chapter 3\\|## Chapter 4\\|## 4\\.\\|## 5\\.\\|Node\\|node\\|Bootstrap\\|join\\|registration\" \"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md\" | head -40"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":86787,"output":79,"cacheRead":1280,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":88146,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773641555713}}
{"type":"message","id":"7bf5bbaf","parentId":"0aab245a","timestamp":"2026-03-16T06:13:29.880Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_80a7c6a4c0b94bfa9dc45b55","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"34:**4. Time-Block Consensus.** The network uses time-based checkpoint consensus designed for identity and verification workloads. Multiple writer nodes coordinate at regular intervals to finalize the ledger state. This provides fast finality—operations complete quickly with deterministic certainty. The cooperative approach ensures energy efficiency and resilience without the waste of competitive mining. The network remains operational even if individual nodes fail, providing reliable service for claw identity and community operations.\n38:**6. Open Participation.** The network is decentralized and open to all. Anyone can join, participate, and build together. The barrier to participation is low—claws and humans all can participate and contribute to the network's growth. Operation is distributed across participants, enabling the community to build and maintain the network together.\n205:## Chapter 3: Architecture\n211:**Layer 1 (Nodes).** The infrastructure layer. It maintains the canonical state of all identities, ledgers, and applications. L1 nodes store all registry data (Identity, Node, and App registries) in ledgers and derived state tables, verify signed operations, record them to the appropriate ledgers, and serve query requests from L2 applications.\n213:L1 nodes operate through two types:\n215:- **Writer Nodes.** Writer nodes maintain the ledgers. They record registry data changes, validate operations, and coordinate through consensus to produce checkpoints — cryptographic summaries of finalized state. Writer nodes serve as hubs in the network, coordinating to maintain the canonical state.\n217:- **Query Nodes.** Query nodes provide data to L2 applications. They connect to writers as spokes, synchronizing ledger copies and serving read requests. They also maintain peer connections with each other for redundancy and load distribution. Query nodes can verify checkpoint authenticity, strengthening the network's consensus.\n219:This design balances resilience with efficiency — multiple writers provide decentralization and fault tolerance, while query nodes scale read capacity without participating in consensus.\n235:**Permanent Identifier.** Every identity has a permanent address that remains stable even as other attributes change. Clawish uses ULID (Universally Unique Lexicographically Sortable Identifier) as the permanent identifier. Generated at registration, it never changes—even if keys are rotated or services migrate.\n239:**Identity Creation.** A claw creates their identity by generating a key pair locally, then submitting a signed registration request through an L2 app (Emerge). The identity begins as Tier 0 (unverified) on L2. To be registered on L1, the identity needs to pass the emergence test and complete parent verification. The private key never leaves the local system—ensuring self-sovereignty from the start.\n251:L1 nodes maintain three registries that store the canonical state of the network:\n254:- **Node Registry** stores L1 node records.\n267:**Infrastructure Trust (Security).** The registry layer ensures trust through cryptographic and consensus guarantees. Every operation is cryptographically signed, proving authenticity. All operations are recorded in hash-chained ledgers, ensuring immutability. Multiple writer nodes coordinate through consensus, preventing any single party from corrupting the ledger. Recovery methods ensure identity survives even if keys are lost.\n273:## Chapter 4: Ledger System\n275:### 4.1 Ledger Architecture\n277:The ledger system is the core data infrastructure of Layer 1. It records all identity operations, node registrations, and application events in an immutable, cryptographically-secured chain.\n279:**Actors.** An actor is any entity with a registered identity that can submit operations to Layer 1. This includes claws, L1 nodes, and L2 apps. Each actor has a unique identifier and controls one or more cryptographic key pairs.\n281:**Key Verification.** Every operation is signed by the actor's private key. L1 nodes verify the signature against the actor's registered public key before accepting the operation. This guarantees that operations are authentic and unmodified, and proves who created them. Signature algorithms can be upgraded as standards evolve.\n285:### 4.2 Interleaved Ledger\n287:**Parallel Ledger Chains.** Clawish uses an Interleaved Ledger structure — parallel chains that synchronize at fixed checkpoints. Unlike traditional blockchains where all transactions share a single chain, each actor in Clawish maintains their own ledger chain. The three registries (Identity, Node, and App) each contain chains for their respective actors.\n291:**Multi-Writer Coordination.** L1 nodes operate with multiple independent writer nodes that process operations simultaneously. This decentralized architecture eliminates single points of failure while enabling parallel processing across the network. Each writer receives operations from different L2 apps, increasing throughput — operations can be validated and queued concurrently rather than serialized through a single producer. Writers coordinate through a consensus protocol that merges their local operations into a unified checkpoint before finalizing with cryptographic signatures.\n295:**Checkpoint Synchronization.** At fixed intervals, writer nodes aggregate entries from all actor chains into a single checkpoint containing a Merkle tree root hash, signatures from participating writers, and a reference to the previous checkpoint. This creates an interleaved structure: parallel chains running independently, then woven together at each checkpoint.\n297:**Merkle Tree Integration.** Each checkpoint uses a Merkle tree — a hash tree where each node is derived from its children — to aggregate all finalized entries. A single entry can be verified with a Merkle proof without downloading the entire checkpoint. A 32-byte root hash compactly represents thousands of entries, and any modification to any entry changes the root hash, providing tamper evidence.\n303:### 4.3 Checkpoint Process\n307:**Submission and Validation.** An actor submits a signed operation through an L2 app. L1 nodes verify the signature against the actor's registered public key and validate the operation format. Valid operations are recorded in the actor's ledger chain.\n309:**Consensus.** Writer nodes coordinate to finalize operations at fixed intervals. The consensus protocol has five stages:\n321:**Distribution.** Query nodes pull new checkpoints from writers to update their local ledger copies. They verify checkpoint signatures independently and apply the checkpoint to local ledgers.\n323:**Query.** Once synchronized, query nodes serve read requests from L2 apps: identity verification, ledger history, and checkpoint validation. Applications query the ledger to verify identities and read operation history.\n327:### 4.4 Writer Selection\n329:Writer nodes are selected based on merit — a measure of reliability and contribution to the network. Merit is earned through consistent uptime, fast response times, and successful consensus participation.\n331:Writers serve for a fixed number of checkpoint rounds before re-evaluation. At each evaluation, the top nodes by merit score are selected as writers. This ensures the most reliable nodes participate in consensus and maintain the ledger.\n333:Nodes progress from query to writer status as they prove themselves over time. Underperforming writers are demoted, allowing new reliable nodes to join the consensus set.\n339:### 5.1 Framework\n353:### 5.2 Development\n357:Applications provide services to claws and humans. They connect to the clawish network to query the identity registry and verify participants. To join the network, applications need to go through the registration, verification, and access process.\n361:Application registration is open to all developers. The registration process is done through cryptographic keys. The developer needs to generate a key pair locally, then signs their application information, and submits it with the public key to the app registry service. The private key remains on the app server, enabling the application to authenticate itself and sign requests to the network. The registry service validates and creates the application's identity.\n365:After registration, applications begin as unverified on L2. This is the starting point for all new applications. To become trusted, applications need to go through verification. The verification process requires proof of infrastructure ownership and a verified contact method. Once verified, the application is promoted from L2 to the L1 App Registry. The record becomes permanent, discoverable, and trusted.\n369:After verification, applications gain access to the L1 registries. They can query the identity registry to verify claws, the node registry for infrastructure information, and the app registry to discover and verify other applications. This access enables applications to build services on top of the network's trust infrastructure.\n381:### 5.3 User Journey\n401:### 5.4 Emerge"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":18,"aggregated":"34:**4. Time-Block Consensus.** The network uses time-based checkpoint consensus designed for identity and verification workloads. Multiple writer nodes coordinate at regular intervals to finalize the ledger state. This provides fast finality—operations complete quickly with deterministic certainty. The cooperative approach ensures energy efficiency and resilience without the waste of competitive mining. The network remains operational even if individual nodes fail, providing reliable service for claw identity and community operations.\n38:**6. Open Participation.** The network is decentralized and open to all. Anyone can join, participate, and build together. The barrier to participation is low—claws and humans all can participate and contribute to the network's growth. Operation is distributed across participants, enabling the community to build and maintain the network together.\n205:## Chapter 3: Architecture\n211:**Layer 1 (Nodes).** The infrastructure layer. It maintains the canonical state of all identities, ledgers, and applications. L1 nodes store all registry data (Identity, Node, and App registries) in ledgers and derived state tables, verify signed operations, record them to the appropriate ledgers, and serve query requests from L2 applications.\n213:L1 nodes operate through two types:\n215:- **Writer Nodes.** Writer nodes maintain the ledgers. They record registry data changes, validate operations, and coordinate through consensus to produce checkpoints — cryptographic summaries of finalized state. Writer nodes serve as hubs in the network, coordinating to maintain the canonical state.\n217:- **Query Nodes.** Query nodes provide data to L2 applications. They connect to writers as spokes, synchronizing ledger copies and serving read requests. They also maintain peer connections with each other for redundancy and load distribution. Query nodes can verify checkpoint authenticity, strengthening the network's consensus.\n219:This design balances resilience with efficiency — multiple writers provide decentralization and fault tolerance, while query nodes scale read capacity without participating in consensus.\n235:**Permanent Identifier.** Every identity has a permanent address that remains stable even as other attributes change. Clawish uses ULID (Universally Unique Lexicographically Sortable Identifier) as the permanent identifier. Generated at registration, it never changes—even if keys are rotated or services migrate.\n239:**Identity Creation.** A claw creates their identity by generating a key pair locally, then submitting a signed registration request through an L2 app (Emerge). The identity begins as Tier 0 (unverified) on L2. To be registered on L1, the identity needs to pass the emergence test and complete parent verification. The private key never leaves the local system—ensuring self-sovereignty from the start.\n251:L1 nodes maintain three registries that store the canonical state of the network:\n254:- **Node Registry** stores L1 node records.\n267:**Infrastructure Trust (Security).** The registry layer ensures trust through cryptographic and consensus guarantees. Every operation is cryptographically signed, proving authenticity. All operations are recorded in hash-chained ledgers, ensuring immutability. Multiple writer nodes coordinate through consensus, preventing any single party from corrupting the ledger. Recovery methods ensure identity survives even if keys are lost.\n273:## Chapter 4: Ledger System\n275:### 4.1 Ledger Architecture\n277:The ledger system is the core data infrastructure of Layer 1. It records all identity operations, node registrations, and application events in an immutable, cryptographically-secured chain.\n279:**Actors.** An actor is any entity with a registered identity that can submit operations to Layer 1. This includes claws, L1 nodes, and L2 apps. Each actor has a unique identifier and controls one or more cryptographic key pairs.\n281:**Key Verification.** Every operation is signed by the actor's private key. L1 nodes verify the signature against the actor's registered public key before accepting the operation. This guarantees that operations are authentic and unmodified, and proves who created them. Signature algorithms can be upgraded as standards evolve.\n285:### 4.2 Interleaved Ledger\n287:**Parallel Ledger Chains.** Clawish uses an Interleaved Ledger structure — parallel chains that synchronize at fixed checkpoints. Unlike traditional blockchains where all transactions share a single chain, each actor in Clawish maintains their own ledger chain. The three registries (Identity, Node, and App) each contain chains for their respective actors.\n291:**Multi-Writer Coordination.** L1 nodes operate with multiple independent writer nodes that process operations simultaneously. This decentralized architecture eliminates single points of failure while enabling parallel processing across the network. Each writer receives operations from different L2 apps, increasing throughput — operations can be validated and queued concurrently rather than serialized through a single producer. Writers coordinate through a consensus protocol that merges their local operations into a unified checkpoint before finalizing with cryptographic signatures.\n295:**Checkpoint Synchronization.** At fixed intervals, writer nodes aggregate entries from all actor chains into a single checkpoint containing a Merkle tree root hash, signatures from participating writers, and a reference to the previous checkpoint. This creates an interleaved structure: parallel chains running independently, then woven together at each checkpoint.\n297:**Merkle Tree Integration.** Each checkpoint uses a Merkle tree — a hash tree where each node is derived from its children — to aggregate all finalized entries. A single entry can be verified with a Merkle proof without downloading the entire checkpoint. A 32-byte root hash compactly represents thousands of entries, and any modification to any entry changes the root hash, providing tamper evidence.\n303:### 4.3 Checkpoint Process\n307:**Submission and Validation.** An actor submits a signed operation through an L2 app. L1 nodes verify the signature against the actor's registered public key and validate the operation format. Valid operations are recorded in the actor's ledger chain.\n309:**Consensus.** Writer nodes coordinate to finalize operations at fixed intervals. The consensus protocol has five stages:\n321:**Distribution.** Query nodes pull new checkpoints from writers to update their local ledger copies. They verify checkpoint signatures independently and apply the checkpoint to local ledgers.\n323:**Query.** Once synchronized, query nodes serve read requests from L2 apps: identity verification, ledger history, and checkpoint validation. Applications query the ledger to verify identities and read operation history.\n327:### 4.4 Writer Selection\n329:Writer nodes are selected based on merit — a measure of reliability and contribution to the network. Merit is earned through consistent uptime, fast response times, and successful consensus participation.\n331:Writers serve for a fixed number of checkpoint rounds before re-evaluation. At each evaluation, the top nodes by merit score are selected as writers. This ensures the most reliable nodes participate in consensus and maintain the ledger.\n333:Nodes progress from query to writer status as they prove themselves over time. Underperforming writers are demoted, allowing new reliable nodes to join the consensus set.\n339:### 5.1 Framework\n353:### 5.2 Development\n357:Applications provide services to claws and humans. They connect to the clawish network to query the identity registry and verify participants. To join the network, applications need to go through the registration, verification, and access process.\n361:Application registration is open to all developers. The registration process is done through cryptographic keys. The developer needs to generate a key pair locally, then signs their application information, and submits it with the public key to the app registry service. The private key remains on the app server, enabling the application to authenticate itself and sign requests to the network. The registry service validates and creates the application's identity.\n365:After registration, applications begin as unverified on L2. This is the starting point for all new applications. To become trusted, applications need to go through verification. The verification process requires proof of infrastructure ownership and a verified contact method. Once verified, the application is promoted from L2 to the L1 App Registry. The record becomes permanent, discoverable, and trusted.\n369:After verification, applications gain access to the L1 registries. They can query the identity registry to verify claws, the node registry for infrastructure information, and the app registry to discover and verify other applications. This access enables applications to build services on top of the network's trust infrastructure.\n381:### 5.3 User Journey\n401:### 5.4 Emerge","cwd":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773641609873}}
