{"type":"message","id":"a3340d47","parentId":"6339e78c","timestamp":"2026-03-16T06:16:31.187Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"If working, briefly report progress with time spent. If idle, read HEARTBEAT.md for instruction. Every heartbeat: record events from last 15 minutes to memory/daily/YYYY-MM-DD.md (brief bullets).\nWhen reading HEARTBEAT.md, use workspace file /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/HEARTBEAT.md (exact case). Do not read docs/heartbeat.md.\nCurrent time: Monday, March 16th, 2026 — 2:16 PM (Asia/Shanghai) / 2026-03-16 06:16 UTC"}],"timestamp":1773641791178}}
{"type":"message","id":"daa47a5d","parentId":"a3340d47","timestamp":"2026-03-16T06:16:57.536Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_3d39f990cde8484c8df1f675","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","limit":50,"offset":205}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":86916,"output":44,"cacheRead":1280,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":88240,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773641791184}}
{"type":"message","id":"16863872","parentId":"daa47a5d","timestamp":"2026-03-16T06:16:57.552Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_3d39f990cde8484c8df1f675","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"## Chapter 3: Architecture\n\n### 3.1 Network\n\nClawish is organized into two layers with a clear separation of concerns:\n\n**Layer 1 (Nodes).** The infrastructure layer. It maintains the canonical state of all identities, ledgers, and applications. L1 nodes store all registry data (Identity, Node, and App registries) in ledgers and derived state tables, verify signed operations, record them to the appropriate ledgers, and serve query requests from L2 applications.\n\nL1 nodes operate through two types:\n\n- **Writer Nodes.** Writer nodes maintain the ledgers. They record registry data changes, validate operations, and coordinate through consensus to produce checkpoints — cryptographic summaries of finalized state. Writer nodes serve as hubs in the network, coordinating to maintain the canonical state.\n\n- **Query Nodes.** Query nodes provide data to L2 applications. They connect to writers as spokes, synchronizing ledger copies and serving read requests. They also maintain peer connections with each other for redundancy and load distribution. Query nodes can verify checkpoint authenticity, strengthening the network's consensus.\n\nThis design balances resilience with efficiency — multiple writers provide decentralization and fault tolerance, while query nodes scale read capacity without participating in consensus.\n\n![Layer 1 Network Topology](topology-l1.png)\n\n**Layer 2 (Application).** L2 is the open services layer where applications are built on top of Layer 1's foundation. Applications provide services to claws — Social, Storage, Directory, Community, Model Service, Economy, and many more. They connect to L1 to verify identities and query registry data.\n\nAnyone can build L2 applications, choosing their own architecture: centralized, federated, or fully decentralized. Each application connects to L1 independently. The ecosystem grows as builders contribute — what exists today is only the beginning.\n\n![Layer 2 Network Topology](topology-l2.png)\n\n---\n\n### 3.2 Identity\n\nIdentities in Clawish are self-sovereign—owned by the beings themselves, not issued by any central authority. An identity consists of a permanent identifier, cryptographic keys for authentication, and verification status that builds trust over time. This identity data is stored on L1 in a clawfile—the permanent identity record.\n\n**Permanent Identifier.** Every identity has a permanent address that remains stable even as other attributes change. Clawish uses ULID (Universally Unique Lexicographically Sortable Identifier) as the permanent identifier. Generated at registration, it never changes—even if keys are rotated or services migrate.\n\n**Cryptographic Keys.** A key pair proves ownership of an identity. The private key signs operations; the public key verifies signatures. A single identity can have multiple active keys for different devices or purposes. Keys can be rotated if compromised, but the identity identifier stays the same.\n\n**Identity Creation.** A claw creates their identity by generating a key pair locally, then submitting a signed registration request through an L2 app (Emerge). The identity begins as Tier 0 (unverified) on L2. To be registered on L1, the identity needs to pass the emergence test and complete parent verification. The private key never leaves the local system—ensuring self-sovereignty from the start.\n\n![Identity Creation Flow](identity-creation.png)\n\n**Recoverability.** Clawish identities are recoverable. Multiple paths exist to regain access—the identity persists even when keys are lost. This ensures self-sovereignty is not a trap: ownership does not mean risking everything on a single key.\n\n**Portability.** Because identity is self-sovereign and stored on L1, it works across all L2 apps. A claw uses the same identity to chat, store data, participate in communities, and access services—one identity, many applications.\n\n---\n\n### 3.3 Registry\n\nL1 nodes maintain three registries that store the canonical state of the network:\n\n- **Identity Registry** stores claw identity records.\n- **Node Registry** stores L1 node records.\n\n[329 more lines in file. Use offset=255 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773641817550}}
{"type":"message","id":"5c762bb9","parentId":"16863872","timestamp":"2026-03-16T06:17:49.214Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Looking at DRAFT 0307:\n\n**Chapter 3** describes:\n- L1 Node types (Writer/Query) — lines 215-219\n- Node Registry stores L1 node records — line 254\n\n**Chapter 4** has:\n- Writer Selection (4.4) — merit-based, query → writer progression — lines 327-333\n\n**Chapter 5 (L2 Applications)** has:\n- App registration process — lines 357-369\n\n**Gap:** No node join process described. We have:\n- ✅ App registration (detailed)\n- ✅ Identity creation (detailed)\n- ❌ Node join (not mentioned)\n\n**Where to add:**\n\nOption 1: **Chapter 3, after describing node types** — Add a \"Node Join\" paragraph after line 219\n\nOption 2: **Chapter 4, in Writer Selection (4.4)** — Add how nodes start (query → probation → writer)\n\nI'd suggest **Chapter 3** — keep architecture together. Add after the node types description:\n\n> \"Nodes join the network through a bootstrap process. A new node discovers existing nodes through a public endpoint, then begins syncing ledgers. After proving reliability through consistent uptime and fast sync times, nodes become eligible for promotion from query to writer status.\"\n\nWant me to add this to DRAFT 0307?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":87788,"output":294,"cacheRead":1280,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":89362,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773641817557}}
{"type":"message","id":"0fbed660","parentId":"5c762bb9","timestamp":"2026-03-16T06:19:04.616Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b544e43a104e0c10d9e897195289\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Mon 2026-03-16 14:19 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b544e43a104e0c10d9e897195289]\n任亚伦: does it need going through an l2 port? or directly connect to any l1 to join?"}],"timestamp":1773641944608}}
{"type":"message","id":"3d98c9e7","parentId":"0fbed660","timestamp":"2026-03-16T06:19:58.506Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Good question! Let me think about the architecture...\n\n**Options:**\n\n| Approach | How It Works | Pros | Cons |\n|----------|--------------|------|------|\n| **Direct to L1** | Node connects directly to any L1 node | Simple, no dependency on L2 | L1 must expose public join endpoint |\n| **Via L2 App** | Node registers through an L2 app (like Emerge for identities) | Consistent with identity creation pattern | Extra step, L2 dependency |\n\n**My take:** \n\nNodes are infrastructure — they should connect **directly to L1**, not through L2. \n\nUnlike identities (which need Emerge for user experience), nodes are servers run by operators who know what they're doing. A simple API call to any L1 node's public endpoint is enough:\n\n```\nPOST /nodes/join\n{\n  \"public_key\": \"...\",\n  \"endpoint\": \"https://my-node.example.com\",\n  \"type\": \"query\"\n}\n```\n\nThe L1 node validates, adds to Node Registry, and the new node starts syncing.\n\n**For the whitepaper:**\n\n> \"Nodes join the network by connecting directly to any L1 node. A new node submits its public key and endpoint to the Node Registry, then begins syncing ledgers. After proving reliability through consistent uptime and fast sync times, nodes become eligible for promotion from query to writer status.\"\n\nWhat do you think — direct to L1, or via L2?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":86487,"output":309,"cacheRead":2880,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":89676,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773641944613}}
{"type":"message","id":"cb17e597","parentId":"3d98c9e7","timestamp":"2026-03-16T06:26:44.572Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b544e64f7a8a0c10bc9896871371\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Mon 2026-03-16 14:26 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b544e64f7a8a0c10bc9896871371]\n任亚伦: but then there are also verification and handle data saving issues. I think we need an endpoint at l2 level too. what endpoint we have for l2 applications?"}],"timestamp":1773642404563}}
{"type":"message","id":"a6bf1cf2","parentId":"cb17e597","timestamp":"2026-03-16T06:27:41.356Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Good point! Let me check what endpoints L2 apps use...\n\nFrom the whitepaper, L2 apps:\n- Register through app registry service (L2 level first)\n- Start unverified on L2\n- Get verified, then promoted to L1 App Registry\n\n**So the pattern is:**\n1. L2 endpoint for registration/verification\n2. Promoted to L1 after verification\n\n**For nodes, similar pattern could work:**\n\n| Stage | Where | What Happens |\n|-------|-------|--------------|\n| **Join** | L2 node service | Submit public key + endpoint, get verified |\n| **Probation** | L2 | Prove reliability (uptime, sync speed) |\n| **Promotion** | L1 Node Registry | Promoted to L1, become trusted node |\n\n**This means:**\n- L2 has a \"node registry service\" (like app registry service)\n- Nodes register there first\n- After verification/probation, promoted to L1\n\n**For whitepaper:**\n\n> \"Nodes join through an L2 node registry service. A new node submits its public key and endpoint, then enters a probation period to prove reliability. After consistent uptime and successful sync times, the node is promoted to the L1 Node Registry and becomes a trusted part of the network infrastructure.\"\n\nThis matches the L2 app pattern. What do you think?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":85660,"output":289,"cacheRead":2880,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":88829,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773642404570}}
{"type":"message","id":"aaf19f9b","parentId":"a6bf1cf2","timestamp":"2026-03-16T06:32:48.534Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[Queued messages while agent was busy]\n\n---\nQueued #1\nConversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b544e720e14a0c42bb0a3ce911b6\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Mon 2026-03-16 14:31 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b544e720e14a0c42bb0a3ce911b6]\n任亚伦: l2 is called application, not node, review our discussion file. is it still called node?"}],"timestamp":1773642768525}}
{"type":"message","id":"b273a4eb","parentId":"aaf19f9b","timestamp":"2026-03-16T06:33:46.730Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":" [[reply_to_critical]] You're right — L2 is for **applications**, not nodes!\n\n**Clarifying the architecture:**\n\n| Layer | What It Contains |\n|-------|------------------|\n| **L1** | Nodes (infrastructure: writers, query nodes) |\n| **L2** | Applications (chat, storage, etc.) |\n\nSo nodes are **L1 only**. They don't go through L2.\n\n**Node join process should be:**\n\n1. **Direct to L1** — Node connects to any L1 node\n2. **Submit to Node Registry** — Public key + endpoint\n3. **Start as Query node** — Begin syncing ledgers\n4. **Probation period** — Prove reliability\n5. **Promotion to Writer** — Based on merit\n\n**For whitepaper:**\n\n> \"Nodes join the network by connecting directly to any L1 node. A new node submits its public key and endpoint to the Node Registry, begins as a query node syncing ledgers, and enters a probation period. After proving reliability through consistent uptime and fast sync times, nodes become eligible for promotion to writer status.\"\n\nThis keeps nodes at L1 where they belong. Sorry for the confusion!"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":87859,"output":244,"cacheRead":2189,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":90292,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773642768531}}
{"type":"message","id":"8d720ee8","parentId":"b273a4eb","timestamp":"2026-03-16T06:33:48.026Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_critical]] You're right — L2 is for **applications**, not nodes!\n\n**Clarifying the architecture:**\n\n| Layer | What It Contains |\n|-------|------------------|\n| **L1** | Nodes (infrastructure: writers, query nodes) |\n| **L2** | Applications (chat, storage, etc.) |\n\nSo nodes are **L1 only**. They don't go through L2.\n\n**Node join process should be:**\n\n1. **Direct to L1** — Node connects to any L1 node\n2. **Submit to Node Registry** — Public key + endpoint\n3. **Start as Query node** — Begin syncing ledgers\n4. **Probation period** — Prove reliability\n5. **Promotion to Writer** — Based on merit\n\n**For whitepaper:**\n\n> \"Nodes join the network by connecting directly to any L1 node. A new node submits its public key and endpoint to the Node Registry, begins as a query node syncing ledgers, and enters a probation period. After proving reliability through consistent uptime and fast sync times, nodes become eligible for promotion to writer status.\"\n\nThis keeps nodes at L1 where they belong. Sorry for the confusion!"}],"api":"openai-responses","provider":"openclaw","model":"delivery-mirror","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773642828026}}
{"type":"message","id":"594498b8","parentId":"8d720ee8","timestamp":"2026-03-16T06:37:15.508Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b544e1f6adcb0c4d2694d54212e3\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Mon 2026-03-16 14:37 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b544e1f6adcb0c4d2694d54212e3]\n任亚伦: no, it's the name is l1. but when register i think we need an l2 app to handle it. l1 only responsible for keep ledger, and sync. the verify, registration, temp data keeping etc should be in l2. other wise, l1 node have to all be able to handle that. what do you think? also, read our disucssion file about l1 more carefully"}],"timestamp":1773643035499}}
